\n</div>\r\n\r\n///\r\n\r\n<div id=\"on-song-1\" class=\"image-holder\" images=\"\">\r\n    <img class=\"\" src=\"/media/jpg/SE_OnSong_on_VOG_15x18_Final.jpg\">\r\n</div>\r\n///\r\n\r\n<div id=\"on-song-2\" class=\"image-holder overlap-image-holder\" zindex=\"1\">\r\n    <img class=\"\" src=\"/media/jpg/SE_Record_IMG_5615_V2_42x50_Final.jpg\">\r\n    <img class=\"\" src=\"/media/jpg/SE_OnSong_on_VOG_15x18_Final.jpg\">\r\n    <img class=\"\" src=\"/media/jpg/SE_OnTrespassing_no_VOG_15x18_Final.jpg\">\r\n    <img class=\"\" src=\"/media/jpg/SE_OnTrespassing_no_VOG_15x18_Final_1.jpg\">\r\n    <img class=\"\" src=\"/media/jpg/SE_OnTrespassing_pass_V2_15x31_Final.jpg\">\r\n    <img class=\"\" src=\"/media/jpg/SE_OnTrespassing_tres_VOG_15x32_Final.jpg\">\r\n    <img class=\"\" src=\"/media/jpg/SE_OnTrespassing_Sing_V3_15x30_Final.jpg\">\r\n    <img class=\"\" src=\"/media/jpg/SE_OnTrespassing_ing_V2_15x22_Final.jpg\">\r\n    <img class=\"\" src=\"/media/jpg/SE_OnSong_song_G_V3_8x15_Final.jpg\">\r\n</div>\r\n///\r\n+++\r\n\r\nVI.\r\n///\r\n\r\n<div id=\"wet-words-1\" class=\"image-holder\" images=\"\">\r\n    <img class=\"\" src=\"/media/jpg/SE_Section_3_WetWords_V3_118x178.jpg\">\r\n</div>\r\n<div id=\"wet-words-2\" class=\"image-holder\" images=\"\">\r\n    <img class=\"\" src=\"/media/jpg/hot-field-sec-1.jpg\">\r\n</div>\r\n///\r\n\r\n<div id=\"wet-words-3\" class=\"image-holder image-float-container\" images=\"\">\r\n    <img class=\"\" src=\"/media/jpg/SE_Section_2_1_V1_33x95_File.jpg\">\r\n    <img class=\"\" src=\"/media/jpg/SE_Section_2_2_V1_44x106_File.jpg\">\r\n    <img class=\"\" src=\"/media/jpg/SE_Section_2_3_V3_44x116_File.jpg\">\r\n    <img class=\"\" src=\"/media/jpg/SE_Section_2_4_V2_33x135_File.jpg\">\r\n    <img class=\"\" src=\"/media/jpg/SE_Section_2_5_V1_33x100_File.jpg\">\r\n    <img class=\"\" src=\"/media/jpg/SE_Section_2_6_V1C_33x66_File.jpg\">\r\n</div>\r\n///\r\n\r\n<div id=\"earthly-trio\" class=\"image-holder image-float-container\" images=\"\">\r\n    <img class=\"\" src=\"/media/jpg/quick_IMG_6114.jpg\">\r\n</div>\r\n<div id=\"audio-holder-3\" class=\"audio-holder\">\r\n    <audio id=\"audio-4\" controls=\"\">\r\n        <source src=\"/media/audio/all-at-once-1-4.mp3\" type=\"audio/mp3\">\r\n    </audio>\r\n</div>\r\n///\r\n+++\r\n',_binary '\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								'),(15,1,'2021-03-04 16:02:31','2021-05-25 16:25:07',80,'Colophon',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'colophon',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,_binary '\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								',_binary '<div class=\"columns\">\r\n<div>COLOPHON</div><div><br></div><div><div>The STRAY WORLD website is published through SOURCE TYPE, an Office for Typographic Research &amp; Visual Literacy based in Zürich, Switzerland.</div></div><div><br></div><div>Text &amp; Images: Shannon Ebner</div><div>Design: David Reinfurt</div><div>Programming: Wei-Hao Wang<br></div><div>Copy editing: Robert Dewhurst<br></div><div><div>Typography for Section VI: Helvetica Autospace by Mark Owens and Nilas Andersen, with photographic modifications by Shannon Ebner</div><div>Additional Typography: Laurenz Brunner &amp; Ben Schwartz</div></div><div><br></div><div>The work produced for ‘Beautiful World, Where Are You?’, was commissioned by the Liverpool Biennial 2018. Special thanks to Kitty Scott and Tom McDonough.</div><div><br></div><div>Portions of this project were made possible by research funds from the Canter Arts Center at Stanford University. Thanks to Alison Gass and Susan Dackerman for their support.</div><div><br></div><div>PROJECT CHRONOLOGY</div><div><br></div><div>2019<span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">	</span></div><div>WET WORDS IN A HOT FIELD, Altman Siegel Gallery, San Francisco</div><div>A GRAPHIC TONE, kaufmann repetto, Milan</div><div>STRAY: A GRAPHIC TONE, Cantor Arts Center, Stanford University</div><div><a href=\"https://fonografeditions.com/catalog/stray-a-graphic-tone/\">STRAY: A GRAPHIC TONE</a>, an LP featuring Susan Howe and Nathaniel Mackey, (<span style=\"font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;;\">Fonograf Editions / <a href=\"https://www.romapublications.org/Roma201-400.html\">Roma Publications</a></span>)</div><div><br></div><div>2018</div><div>THE SEVEN SLEEPERS, Liverpool Biennial 2018</div><div><br></div><div>2017</div><div>STRAY, Eva Presenhuber, New York</div><div><br></div><div><div>A NOTE ON THE TYPE</div><div><br></div><div>The Wet Letter alphabet was made in the former recording studios of the electropop band LCD Soundsystem, in the West Village. As the building was in the early stages of a renovation project, it was also in the process of being slowly vacated by the band members. It had that liminal charge that spaces have when they are in a process of changeover, with bits of life and living strewn about its floors and walls. A friend who had recently taken possession of the building lent me but one small key to open its front door, and I would go there to photograph a set of paper letters that were about the size of my outstretched hand. I would wander the floors of the building conducting a series of alphabetic tests while studying the light, “pasting” letters around the space with nothing more than a pail of water. This was a delicate act. I would put the letters up with water, and by the time I got from A to Z the first soldiers would have dried and fallen to the ground. Sometimes weeks would pass between my tests and I would return to find the letters in motionless disarray. I would collect the small characters, lifting them from the ground where they lay quiet and shopworn. Revived by water, they would come back to life quickly, ready to sign, ready to signal; a practice of outside conducted from the inside.&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div>The typeface for the Wet Letter alphabet was derived from Helvetica Monospace, which was then modified by the designers Mark Owens and Nilas Andersen, for a version they renamed Helvetica Autospace for a project we made together in 2014. I reached for this typeface in my own time of transition, as I relocated from Los Angeles, where I had lived for eighteen years, to New York, where I had lived during the nineties when I was in my twenties. It was as if the bed of Los Angeles were still warm, and the typeface—but one symbolic remnant of the city’s built environment of commercial signs, with their chorus of graphic tones—was still holding sway as I made a new way in an old place.</div><div><br></div><div>*</div><div><br></div><div>How can a camera be so sure that its subjects are willing to be seen if not heard, to be in the weather if not destroyed by it, to be in the war if not moving away from it, to be wet words in a hot field.</div></div><div><br></div><div>IMAGE&nbsp;CHECKLIST:</div><div><br></div><div><div>I. WORDS CATCHING AIR</div><div><br></div><div>2.</div><div>PHOTORAMA</div><div>2017</div><div>archival pigment print mounted on aluminum, 2 parts</div><div>each: 36 × 76 in. / 91.5 × 193 cm&nbsp;<br></div><div>both: 72 × 76 in. / 183 × 193 cm</div><div>1/5 + 2 AP<br></div><div><br></div><div>3.</div><div>TEMPLE HIGH AND LO</div><div>2017</div><div>archival pigment print mounted on aluminum</div><div>31.5 × 21 in. / 80 × 53.5 cm<br></div><div>1/5 + 2 AP<br></div><div><br></div><div>4.</div><div>CIRCULAR TIME</div><div><br></div><div>5.</div><div>STRAY</div><div>2017</div><div>archival pigment prints mounted on aluminum, 2 parts&nbsp;</div><div>each: 48 × 36 in. / 122 × 91.5 cm&nbsp;<br></div><div>Left: Susan Howe, “Articulation of Sound Forms in Time,” from SINGULARITIES (Middletown, CT: Wesleyan University Press, 1990)&nbsp;<br></div><div>Right: Nathaniel Mackey, “Song of the Andoumboulou: 50,” from SPLAY ANTHEM (New York: New Directions, 2006)</div><div>1/5 + 2 AP<br></div><div><br></div><div>6.</div><div>FRIENDS IN DEED HOUSE</div><div>2017</div><div>archival pigment print mounted on aluminum, 8 parts</div><div>7 parts, each: 14 × 9 in. / 35.5 × 23 cm&nbsp;</div><div>1 part: 63 × 40.8 in. / 160 × 103.5 cm&nbsp;</div><div>1/5 + 2 AP<br></div><div><br></div><div>7.</div><div>GRACE WALKING AND TALKING</div><div>2017</div><div>archival pigment print mounted on aluminum</div><div>5 × 7.1 in. / 12.5 × 18 cm<br></div><div>1/5 + 2 AP<br></div><div><br></div><div>8.</div><div>BOMBARDO</div><div>2017</div><div>archival pigment print mounted on aluminum</div><div>48 × 36 in. / 122 × 91.5 cm<br></div><div>1/5 + 2 AP<br></div><div><br></div><div>9.</div><div>WILL AND BE GOING TO</div><div>2017</div><div>archival pigment print mounted on aluminum, 2 parts</div><div>each: 63 × 42 in. / 160 × 106.5 cm<br></div><div>3/5 + 2 AP<br></div><div><br></div><div>10.</div><div>SIGNAL ESCAPES</div><div>2017</div><div>archival pigment print mounted on aluminum, 7 parts</div><div>each: 13.5 × 20 in. / 34.5 × 51 cm&nbsp;<br></div><div>1/5 + 2 AP<br></div><div><br></div><div>11.</div><div>TREE ELLIPSES</div><div>2017</div><div>archival pigment print mounted on aluminum, 2 parts</div><div>each: 16 × 10.6 in. / 40.5 × 27 cm&nbsp;<br></div><div>1/5 + 2 AP<br></div><div><br></div><div>12.</div><div>THE SPLAY ANTHEM</div><div>2017</div><div>archival pigment print mounted on aluminum</div><div>10 × 14 in. / 25.5 × 35.5 cm<br></div><div>1/5 + 2 AP<br></div><div><br></div><div>II. BEAUTIFUL WORLD, WHERE ARE YOU?</div><div><br></div><div>1.</div><div>THE DAY SHAPES&nbsp;</div><div>Paul Elliman</div><div><br></div><div>2.</div><div>THE SEVEN SLEEPERS</div><div>2018</div><div>archival pigment prints mounted on aluminum with black paint, 3 parts</div><div>each: 34 × 24 in. / 86.4 × 61 cm</div><div>door: 107 × 50 × 10 × 5 in. / 271.8 × 127 × 25.4 × 12.7 cm</div><div><br></div><div>III. STEREOCILIA</div><div><br></div><div>1.</div><div>GROUP HOME</div><div><br></div><div>2.</div><div>A-SIDE</div><div>2018</div><div>archival pigment print mounted on aluminum</div><div>78.5 × 57 × 0.3 in. / 199.4 × 144.8 × 0.8 cm</div><div><br></div><div>A-SIDE: Original floor design by Elizabeth LeCompte from the Wooster Group’s production EARLY SHAKER SPIRITUALS: A RECORD ALBUM</div><div>INTERPRETATION. Photographed at the Performing Garage, New York, July 5,</div><div>2018.</div><div><br></div><div>B-SIDE</div><div>2018</div><div>archival pigment print mounted on aluminum</div><div>18 × 15.4 × 0.3 in. / 45.7 × 39.1 × 0.8 cm</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>B-SIDE: Original stage design by Elizabeth LeCompte, from the Wooster Group’s production B-SIDE: ”NEGRO FOLKLORE FROM TEXAS STATE</div><div>PRISONS,” A RECORD ALBUM INTERPRETATION. Photographed at the Creative Arts Initiative, University at Buffalo, February 9, 2018.</div><div><br></div><div>3.</div><div>TRANSDUCED</div><div>This sequence of six video stills derives from the same B-SIDE stage set.</div><div>The performer in the images is actor Eric Berryman.</div><div><br></div><div>4.</div><div>STRAYER</div><div>2018</div><div>archival pigment print mounted on aluminum</div><div>50 × 43.4 × 0.3 in. / 127 × 110.2 × 0.8 cm</div><div><br></div><div>5.</div><div>ON TRESPASSSINGING</div><div>2018</div><div>archival pigment print mounted on aluminum, 5 prints</div><div>15 × 247.6 × 0.3 in. / 38.1 × 629 × 0.8 cm (variable length)</div><div><br></div><div>6.</div><div>THREE FELLED TREES</div><div>2018</div><div>archival pigment print mounted on aluminum, 3 prints</div><div>each: 40 × 26.6 × 0.3 in. / 101.6 × 67.7 × 0.8 cm</div><div>all: 40 × 79.8 × 0.3 in. / 101.6 × 202.8 × 0.8 cm&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div>7.</div><div>SIGNAL ESCAPES (REPRISE)</div><div>2018</div><div>archival pigment print mounted on aluminum, 7 prints</div><div>each: 13.5 × 20 × 0.3 in. / 34.3 × 50.8 x 0.8 cm&nbsp;</div><div>all: 137.8 × 236.2 × 0.3 in. / 350 × 600 × 0.8 cm&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div>8.</div><div>ON SONG</div><div>2018</div><div>archival pigment print mounted on aluminum, 4 prints</div><div>15 × 68.9 × 0.3 in. / 38.1 × 175 × 0.8 cm (variable length)&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div>IV. SOIL EROSION</div><div>1. SPLAY ANTHEM (REPRISE)</div><div><br></div><div>V. SINGING DOGS SINGING</div><div><br></div><div>1.</div><div>A GRAPHIC TONE</div><div>2018</div><div>archival pigment print mounted on aluminum, 6 prints</div><div>15 x 236.2 x 0.3 in / 38.1 x 600 x 0.8 cm (variable length)</div><div><br></div><div>2.</div><div>TONE POEM</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div>VI. CONFLICT CAMERA AND THE CAMERA CONFLICT</div><div><br></div><div>1.&nbsp;</div><div>WET WORDS IN A HOT FIELD&nbsp;</div><div>2019</div><div>archival pigment prints on Tyvek</div><div>With thanks to Maziyar Pahlevan</div><div><br></div><div>SECTION 1: A 6-SIDED CAMERA POEM</div><div><br></div><div>PANEL 1</div><div>96 × 26 in. / 243.8 × 66 cm</div><div><br></div><div>PANEL 2</div><div>79 × 26 in. / 200.6 × 66 cm</div><div><br></div><div>PANEL 3</div><div>63 × 26 in. / 160 × 66 cm</div><div><br></div><div>PANELS 4 + 5</div><div>48 × 26 in. + 79 × 26 in. / 121.9 × 66 cm + 200.6 × 66 cm</div><div><br></div><div>SECTION 2: SUBJECT FIELDS&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div>PANEL 1</div><div>33 × 95 in. / 83.8 × 241.3 cm</div><div><br></div><div>PANEL 2</div><div>44 × 106 in. / 111.7 × 269.2 cm&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div>PANEL 3</div><div>44 × 116 in. / 111.7 × 294.6 cm</div><div><br></div><div>PANEL 4&nbsp;</div><div>33 × 135 in. / 83.8 × 342.9 cm</div><div><br></div><div>PANEL 5</div><div>33 × 100 in. / 83.8 × 254 cm</div><div><br></div><div>PANEL 6</div><div>33 × 66 in. / 83.8 × 167.6 cm</div><div><br></div><div>SECTION 3: MULTIPLE EXPOSURES</div><div><br></div><div>PANELS 1 + 2</div><div>118 × 179 in. / 299.7 × 454.6 cm</div><div><br></div><div>2.</div><div>EARTHLY TRIO</div></div>\r\n</div>',_binary '\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								'),(16,1,'2021-03-18 15:33:05','2021-04-12 10:51:44',NULL,'Title page',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'title-page',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,_binary '\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								',_binary '\r\n																								\r\n																								///\r\n<div>APPENDIX</div>',_binary '\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								'),(17,1,'2021-03-18 15:41:31','2021-05-19 15:54:45',90,'Afterword',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'afterword',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,_binary '\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								',_binary '\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								<div class=\"columns\">\r\n<div><div>AFTERWORD</div><div><br></div><div>On March 20, 2020, the State of New York went into a capitally induced coma via “shutdown.” The shutdown was an executive order issued from the offices of the governor on account of mounting infection rates from a new virus called SARS-CoV-2. New York City went on PAUSE, the governor’s term for a stoppage in the flow of goods and services and any activities in which human bodies circulated in space, spreading infection by breathing, talking, kissing, singing, or laughing. The city went dark and quiet, no souls for days, then weeks, then months. Death was in the air.</div><div><br></div><div>New York’s first case of the virus was reported on March 1. The pandemic was declared on March 11. The first virus-related death occurred on March 14. By the time of the shutdown on March 20, over seven thousand total cases of the virus—and almost fifty virus-related deaths—had been recorded in the state.</div><div><br></div><div>I wrote the bulk of this project in the early days of shutdown, with the writing then continuing into the summer—months that saw a staggering number of deaths in the New York City area. I can hardly believe that I managed to do anything during this period.&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;;\">Time was like quicksand, a real substance that lived mostly in my imagination, subsuming my body with an alternately fast and slow pull.&nbsp;</span>I would wake up extremely early to write, or find pockets of writing time at odd hours of the day and on weekends, writing through the work, embedding the photographs and audio tracks directly into the process. In the ’90s I carried around a paperback book called WIRELESS IMAGINATION that had a repeating phrase on the cover which burned a hole in my head: WORDS ARE PICTURES AND PICTURES ARE WORDS.&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div>During the period I am describing, the start of the pandemic in New York City, time was punctuated by frequent collisions of sounds: a near-constant pulse of ambulance sirens that was only to be interrupted by military-grade explosives from a seemingly unending stockpile of fireworks. As if what was happening in people’s homes wasn’t catastrophic enough, nighttime had become weaponized too. March 13 brought the tragic death of Breonna Taylor, a Black medical worker who was shot and killed by Louisville police officers during a completely botched raid on her apartment, and on May 25 police officers in Minneapolis asphyxiated George Floyd. The person I have been working with to make this site, David Reinfurt, put a sign on the public-facing door of his studio on the Lower East Side with Floyd’s dying words in all caps: “I CAN’T BREATHE.” In the height of the turmoil that summer, David remarked that Floyd’s words, which were the same as Eric Garner’s almost seven years earlier and had become a rallying cry of the protests against these wrongful deaths in the weeks of civil unrest that were unfolding, also evoked the respiratory infection of COVID-19. As the city scrambled for respirators to machine-assist breathing, it seemed the entire country was suffocating. &nbsp; &nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div>Another sound filled the airwaves during this time, bells from a church near where I was living. It wasn’t the first time that I had noticed them, but during the shutdown, with the sirens and fireworks blasting, the church bells’ melody became more and more distinct, upbeat notes followed by somber downbeat tones. I assumed there was a correlation to the clock and as the year dragged on, I became more and more obsessed with finding the origin of the tune. It seemed that everywhere I went in Brooklyn, I would hear the same bell melody. After several feeble attempts by internet search or randomly calling around to churches in the area, I finally discovered a musical director in Fort Greene who identified the tune after I hummed it into my phone and sent him the file for identification. The melody is called “Westminster Chimes” or “Cambridge Quarters,” the same series of striking clock bells as is played by Big Ben in London. The musical director ventured to guess that most of what we hear today are recordings of bells being played over loudspeakers. Traditionally, striking clocks had two gear trains—a striking train which operated an internal mechanism that rang the bells, and a timekeeping train which measured the passage of time. As Kari Cwynar and Kendra Sullivan wrote by way of a letter: “People, like words, are part of other people, part of other times. ‘A’ belongs to ‘companion’ and combines to form ‘accompaniment.’ A sound made in company is a song.”</div><div><br></div><div>*</div><div><br></div><div>STRAY WORLD was made between the years of 2016 and 2021. While this site and its companion publication are presented under one title, the work was exhibited over time in different places, with each part bearing its own title within the larger whole.&nbsp;</div></div>\r\n</div>',_binary '\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								'),(18,1,'2021-04-12 09:47:30','2021-05-20 13:31:47',60,'On Song',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'on-trespassing',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,_binary '\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								',_binary '<div>ON SONG</div>\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img reversed\" src=\"/media/00021.jpg\">\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img reversed\" src=\"/media/00024.jpg\">\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img\" src=\"/media/00028.jpg\">\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img\" src=\"/media/00021.jpg\">\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img\" src=\"/media/00025.jpg\">\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img\" src=\"/media/00021.jpg\">\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img\" src=\"/media/00023.jpg\">\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img\" src=\"/media/00021.jpg\">\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img\" src=\"/media/00022.jpg\">\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img\" src=\"/media/00024.jpg\">\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img\" src=\"/media/00026.jpg\">\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img\" src=\"/media/00029.jpg\">\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img\" src=\"/media/00031.jpg\">\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img\" src=\"/media/00027.jpg\">\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img\" src=\"/media/00029.jpg\">\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img\" src=\"/media/00030.jpg\">\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img\" src=\"/media/00025.jpg\">\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img\" src=\"/media/00027.jpg\">\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img\" src=\"/media/00029.jpg\">\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img\" src=\"/media/00030.jpg\">\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img\" src=\"/media/00025.jpg\">\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img\" src=\"/media/00027.jpg\">\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img\" src=\"/media/00026.jpg\">\r\n///\r\n<img class=\"trespassing-img\" src=\"/media/00029.jpg\">',_binary '\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								'),(19,1,'2021-05-19 15:50:57','2021-05-20 11:27:17',70,'Splay Anthem (Reprise)',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'splay-anthem-reprise',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,_binary '\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								',_binary '\r\n																								\r\n																								<div>SPLAY ANTHEM (REPRISE)<br></div><div><div><br></div><div>Sometime in the early aughts, I thought it would be funny to run around Los Angeles with a 35 mm camera holding a small sign in front of the lens bearing these two words: AMERICAN PHOTOGRAPHS, the name of a photography book, that is also an essay, and that was published in 1938 by Walker Evans, photography’s paternal figure extraordinaire.</div><div><br></div><div>Still new to the city, I went out to photograph the places around town that I kept noticing by car and which took up similar vernacular tropes to Evans’s magnum opus—car culture, found language, the gasoline station, and architecture. Instead of the churches riddled all over the streets of Evans’s book, I photographed the former Jewish section of East Los Angeles, which is where I happened to be living at the time. City Terrace was adjacent to Boyle Heights, an area that would later be decried for gentrification and artist whitewashing as a gallery scene emerged that threatened to displace the Latinx and Japanese American communities it had been home to ever since the Jews and Blacks relocated to other, western parts of the city in the ’40s and ’50s. The site I photographed in Boyle Heights was a boarded-up and scaffolded brick building, a shul called Talmud Torah Synagogue, built in 1923. A void at the top of the building in the shape of a Torah revealed its former identity as a Jewish site of worship.</div><div><br></div><div>During this same camera outing, I also recall photographing a woman living on the street outside a corporate copy shop in the Mid-Wilshire district. This was a complete taboo for anyone who came of age in the bright lights and long shadows of postmodernism’s maternal order, but I did it anyway. It was as if my sign were a mask for the ghosts of Evans, the broken conscience of Martha Rosler, the animal spirit of Sherrie Levine, and some version of myself that embodied all four of us, but poorly. It was a short-lived project for which I only photographed three rolls of film. I never made actual prints from the scans, but they are images that I return to like an old notebook, looking for evidence of something.</div><div><br></div><div>Perhaps it is simply that the images are the first indication of a fickle relationship that I would come to develop with Walker Evans, a figure whom, as a student, I always dismissed outright, finding the work dull, unemotive, and overrated by the male photography educators who most alienated my sensibilities and intellectual curiosities as a young queer artist coming of age during the Reagan years and AIDS crisis. As for the sign, it went into semiretirement for a handful of years until I pulled it from a pile of things and propped it onto the wall of my studio one day. It lived like that, commenting on everything and nothing in its periphery, until I photographed it as its own thing, an act which by default made it a new thing.</div><div><br></div><div>In 2017, while preparing for a show that I curated called SOIL EROSION, I started to embark on more research about Evans. The show was inspired by the juxtaposition of two images and two sets of words. The first was a silver gelatin print of Evans’s Farm Security Administration work that I had purchased from the Library of Congress. Generically titled SOIL EROSION, Evans worked on his FSA project for brief periods of time between the years of 1935 and 1938. Geographically speaking, he mostly concentrated his efforts in the southeastern United States, with the exceptions of New York City, the coal-mining towns of West Virginia, and the industrial towns of Pennsylvania. His southeastern tour comprised towns in Mississippi, Georgia, Louisiana, and South Carolina. My photograph was part of a larger collection documenting “towns and farms in Mississippi from 1935–1936.”</div><div><br></div><div>In addition to evidence of soil erosion due to floods, Evans’s images also depict farmers, farm scenes, a railroad station, Victorian houses, general stores, storefronts, and signage. A collection of images referred to as “negro quarters” shows former slave quarters in Tupelo, Mississippi, including houses, street scenes, and an image of Black children on barren farm-land. At least one or more of these images made it into AMERICAN PHOTOGRAPHS.</div><div><br></div><div>The second image the show pivoted around was by a former college classmate named Seth Rubin. Double exposed by the camera and underexposed in the printing process, the body of the photographer was rendered almost featureless, with its cause of action unclear. Appearing twice on a pile of felled branches and lying just above the soil line, the photograph always haunted me, existing somewhere between the prefix of the word erosion, EROS-, and its opposite, THE DEATH DRIVE, with its suffix -ION, denoting ACTION or CONDITION, COMMUNION, or UNION.</div><div><br></div><div>Perhaps one of the most consequential discoveries I made during the time I was preparing SOIL EROSION was from an archived lecture that I stumbled upon. Testing the whereabouts of the eros in Evans’s work, and after reading some letters that Evans had written to a male colleague in which he continually disparaged a string of aggrieved relationships with women, I found myself wondering about the nature of Evans’s sexuality—if what I was perceiving was a textbook example of closeted behaviorisms, not to mention the subtexts of certain images that longingly looked at other male subjects. Was Evans’s infamous Holden Caufield-esque alienation really just a beard for his own latent homosexuality? It suddenly seemed so visible that I took my query to the internet, and to my surprise was sent to the distinguished art historian John Tagg, and a lecture that he had delivered, called “KNOCKING AROUND BETWEEN MONEY, SEX, AND BOREDOM”: WALKER EVANS IN HAVANA AND NEW YORK. Tagg’s lecture was delivered on location at the Yale Center for British Art and cosponsored by the Yale University Art Gallery, where he was then a visiting scholar. When I wrote Tagg to ask him about the lecture and share my mutual intrigue, he thanked me for my response:</div><div><br></div><blockquote>Not least since the Yale lecture attracted its share of outrage and hate mail. Perhaps it was too provocative for former students and colleagues, right there where he had taught. Yet, it is in fact the hagiographic view of Evans that diminishes him, rather than the attempt to pursue what has been excluded from the approved engagement<span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">	</span>with his photographs. He is simply not the monolithic moral paragon others invented––and that, for me, makes his work stranger and more compelling.</blockquote><div>I must admit that Tagg’s lecture, and his reply to my query, both dazzled and startled my expectations. For a medium so adept at framing exclusion, if such a thing is possible and with photograph it actually is, Tagg’s speculations about Evan’s sexuality were revelatory.&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div>As Tagg revealed in his lecture, while mainstream narratives around Evans work have often noted its “style of detachment and record”, he “chose to turn to that other great forbidden topic in the canonization of Evans as a man of taste: sex––not in order to out the man or sully his reputation but to ask how this second silence [“NO POLITICS whatever” being the first] also impoverishes our encounter with his work, bleaching it out and rendering it cold and aloof.”&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div>In ‘knocking around’ these untraversed parts of the photographer’s psychic desire, Tagg reconstructs Evans’s cool, and solitary derives through a hot and heavy Havana as that of a camera-in-hand-figure succumbing to the “scopic drive” and “compulsive will to see” that is the medium’s modus operandi. In the final slides of his talk, Tagg deposits us behind the camera with Evans. We see an unnamed male [Nude Study] from the 1930s and we listen to Tagg as he imagines Walker Evans looking at a world on the ground glass of a view camera that is upside down and backwards, magical and secretive, saying that it is as if “suddenly, beneath the sheet” that this is where Evans might possibly “feel in place.”</div></div><div><br></div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<!--\r\n<blockquote><div class=\"section\">1<br>SPLAY ANTHEM (REPRISE)</div><blockquote>Sometime in the early aughts, I thought it would be funny to run around Los Angeles with a 35 mm camera holding a small sign in front of the lens bearing these two words:&nbsp;<blockquote>AMERICAN&nbsp;<br>PHOTO-&nbsp;<br>GRAPHS,</blockquote>the name of a photography book, that is also an essay, and that was published in 1938 by Walker Evans, photography’s paternal figure extraordinaire.&nbsp;<br><br>Still new to the city, I went out to photograph the places around town that I kept noticing by car and which took up similar vernacular tropes to Evans’s magnum opus—car culture, found language, the gasoline station, and architecture. Instead of the churches riddled all over the streets of Evans’s book, I photographed the former Jewish section of East Los Angeles, which is where I happened to be living at the time.&nbsp;<br><br>City Terrace was adjacent to Boyle Heights, an area that would later be decried for gentrification and artist whitewashing as a gallery scene emerged that threatened to displace the Latinx and Japanese American communities it had been home to ever since the Jews and Blacks relocated to other, western parts of the city in the ’40s and ’50s. The site I photographed in Boyle Heights was a boarded-up and scaffolded brick building, a shul called Talmud Torah Synagogue, built in 1923. A void at the top of the building in the shape of a Torah revealed its former identity as a Jewish site of worship.&nbsp;<br><br>I also recalled that I photographed a woman living on the street outside a corporate copy shop in the Mid-Wilshire district. This was a complete taboo for anyone such as myself, who came of age in the bright lights and long shadows of postmodernism’s maternal order, but I did it anyway. It was as if my sign were a mask for the ghosts of Evans, the broken conscience of Martha Rosler, and some version of myself that embodied all three of us, but poorly.&nbsp;<br><br>It was a short-lived project for which I only photographed three rolls of film. I have but a few scanned files to show for it. I never made actual prints from the scans, but they are nevertheless images I return to like an old notebook, looking for evidence of something.&nbsp;<br><br>Perhaps it is simply that the images are the first indication of a fickle relationship that I would come to develop with Walker Evans, a figure whom, as a student, I always dismissed outright, finding the work dull, unemotive, and overrated by the male photography educators who most alienated my sensibilities and intellectual curiosities as a young queer artist coming of age during the Reagan years and AIDS crisis.<br><br>As for the sign, it went into semiretirement for a handful of years until I pulled it from a pile of things and propped it onto the wall of my studio one day. It lived like that, commenting on everything and nothing in its periphery, until I photographed it as its own thing, an act which by default made it a new thing.</blockquote></blockquote>\r\n\r\n<blockquote><div class=\"section\">2<br>SOIL<br>EROS-<br>ION</div><blockquote>In 2017, while preparing for a group show I curated called SOIL EROSION, I started to embark on more research about Evans. The show was inspired by the juxtaposition of two images and two sets of words. The first was an 11 × 14 inch silver gelatin print of Evans’s Farm Security Administration work that I had purchased from the Library of Congress. Generically titled <blockquote>SOIL EROSION,</blockquote></blockquote></blockquote>\r\n\r\n<blockquote><blockquote>it was taken in 1936 somewhere in the vicinity of Jackson, Mississippi. Evans worked on his FSA project for brief periods of time between the years of 1935 and 1938. Geographically speaking, he mostly concentrated his efforts in the southeastern United States, with the exceptions of New York City, the coal-mining towns of West Virginia, and the industrial towns of Pennsylvania. His southeastern tour comprised towns in Mississippi, Georgia, Louisiana, and South Carolina. My photograph was part of a larger collection documenting “towns and farms in Mississippi from 1935–1936.”<br><br>In addition to evidence of soil erosion due to floods, Evans’s images also depict farmers, farm scenes, a railroad station, Victorian houses, general stores, storefronts, and signage. A collection of images referred to as “negro quarters” shows former slave quarters in Tupelo, Mississippi, including houses, street scenes, and an image of Black children on barren farm land. At least one or more of these images made it into <blockquote>AMERICAN PHOTOGRAPHS.</blockquote>The second image my show pivoted around was a self-portrait of a former college classmate named Seth Rubin, circa 1991. Double exposed by the camera and underexposed in the printing process, the male body of the photographer was rendered almost featureless, with its cause of action unclear. Whereas most of the images that Rubin made at this time depicted him naked and rolling in mud, in this image he appeared twice on a pile of felled branches, lying just above the soil line. The photograph always haunted me, existing somewhere between the prefix of the word <i>erosion</i>, <blockquote>EROS-,</blockquote>and its opposite,<blockquote>THE DEATH DRIVE,</blockquote>with its suffix<blockquote>-ION,</blockquote>denoting<blockquote>ACTION</blockquote> or <blockquote>CONDITION,</blockquote><blockquote>COMMUNION,</blockquote> or <blockquote>UNION.</blockquote>Perhaps one of the most consequential discoveries I made during the time I was preparing <blockquote>SOIL EROSION </blockquote>was from an archived lecture that I stumbled upon. Testing the whereabouts of the eros in Evans’s work, and after reading some letters that Evans had written to a male colleague in which he continually disparaged a string of aggrieved relationships with women, I found myself wondering about the nature of Evans’s sexuality—if what I was perceiving was a textbook example of closeted behaviorisms, not to mention the subtexts of certain images that longingly looked at other male subjects.&nbsp;<br><br>Was Evans’s infamous alienation really just a beard for his own latent homosexuality? It suddenly seemed so visible that I took my query to the internet, and to my surprise was sent to the distinguished art historian John Tagg, and a lecture that he had delivered, called<blockquote>KNOCKING AROUND BETWEEN MONEY, SEX, AND BOREDOM: WALKER EVANS IN HAVANA AND NEW YORK.</blockquote>Tagg’s lecture was delivered on location at the Yale Center for British Art and cosponsored by the Yale University Art Gallery, where he was then a visiting scholar. When I wrote Tagg to ask him about the lecture and share my mutual intrigue, he thanked me for my response:</blockquote></blockquote>\r\n\r\n<blockquote><blockquote><blockquote>Not least since the Yale lecture attracted its share of outrage and hate mail. Perhaps it was too provocative for former students and colleagues, right there where he had taught. Yet, it is in fact the hagiographic view of Evans that diminishes him, rather than the attempt to pursue what has been excluded from the approved engagement with his photographs. He is simply not the monolithic moral paragon others invented––and that, for me, makes his work stranger and more compelling.</blockquote><br><br>The original call for <blockquote>SOIL EROSION </blockquote>sought to maneuver around its title. It spoke of states’ erosions, climate erosions, cultural erosions, and social erosions. Soil as land, body, and soiling. Erosion as eros, loss, and desire, and also the potential for new clearings. &nbsp;<br><br>In the days, weeks, and now years following the 2016 presidential election, this phraseology has entered into shifting landscapes that with each passing day grow more and more unimaginable, where any idea of ground or grounding is unclear at best. &nbsp;<br><br>Taken together, the work in <blockquote>SOIL EROSION </blockquote>was a collection of these starting points placed in a larger narrative field where meaning plus the cultural and political circumstances of our living conditions went to work on each other to cast doubt and shore up new certainties.</blockquote></blockquote>\r\n-->',_binary '\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								\r\n																								');
